          </div>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">With a 30% balloon, monthly repayments drop by approximately 25–30%. For the Ford Ranger Wildtrak at $65,000, a 30% balloon ($19,500) brings monthly repayments down to approximately $891/month — a saving of $381/month. The $19,500 balloon is due at the end of year 5.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Ute Finance for Tradies and Self-Employed</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">If you are a tradesperson, contractor, or self-employed and the ute is your primary work vehicle, a chattel mortgage is almost certainly the best structure. The tax savings compound: GST recovery puts cash back immediately, interest deductions reduce your taxable income each year, depreciation further reduces your tax bill, and any ute accessories fitted for work (tool boxes, canopies, roof racks, bull bars) can often be included in the finance and depreciated.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">For tradies who are newly self-employed or have limited financial documentation, low doc chattel mortgage options are available. These accept 3–6 months of bank statements or BAS instead of full tax returns. Rates are slightly higher (typically 0.5–2% above full doc rates), but the tax benefits of a chattel mortgage still make it more favourable than a consumer car loan in most cases.</p>
